<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="212">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34187" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Plagiolepis mediorufa Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediorufa">Plagiolepis mediorufa</taxonomicName>
(Forel)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageNumber="212">
Numerous workers from Stanleyville (Lang and Chapin), taken from the leaf-pouches of Cola Laurentii. This form was originally described as a simple variety of the Palearctic 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34198" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Plagiolepis pygmaea (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaea">P. pygmaea (Latreille)</taxonomicName>
, from specimens taken by Kohl &quot;dans une plante myrmecophile,&quot; near Stanleyville. It should, in my opinion, be regarded as a distinct species on account of its peculiar habitat, for pygmsea nests in the soil under stones. Moreover, the worker 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34187" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Plagiolepis mediorufa Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediorufa">mediorufa</taxonomicName>
is decidedly smaller, with much shorter antennae, the median funicular joints especially being distinctly shorter than long, whereas in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34198" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Plagiolepis pygmaea (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaea">pygmaea</taxonomicName>
they are longer than broad. The head is proportionally smaller and narrower, with more rounded sides and with the occipital border straight or slightly convex, not concave as in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34198" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Plagiolepis pygmaea (Latreille)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaea">pygmaea</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
